      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from sklearn.gaussian_process import GaussianProcessRegressor\n",
        "from sklearn.gaussian_process.kernels import RBF, ConstantKernel as C, WhiteKernel\n",
        "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
        "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",
        "from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score\n",
        "import kagglehub\n",
        "\n",
        "# 1. Download and load the dataset\n",
        "kagglepath = \"elikplim/eergy-efficiency-dataset\"\n",
        "path = kagglehub.dataset_download(kagglepath)\n",
        "df = pd.read_csv(path + \"/ENB2012_data.csv\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# 2. Prepare features (X1-X8) and multi-output responses (Y1, Y2)\n",
        "X = df.iloc[:, 0:8].values\n",
        "y = df[['Y1', 'Y2']].values\n",
        "\n",
        "# It is highly recommended to scale inputs for GPR to ensure stable hyperparameter optimization\n",
        "scaler_X = StandardScaler()\n",
        "X_scaled = scaler_X.fit_transform(X)\n",
        "\n",
        "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)\n",
        "\n",
        "# 3. Define the Kernel Structure\n",
        "# RBF kernel handles smoothness, WhiteKernel explicitly models the noise variance (\\sigma_m^2)\n",
        "kernel = C(1.0, (1e-3, 1e3)) * RBF(length_scale=1.0, length_scale_bounds=(1e-2, 1e2)) + WhiteKernel(noise_level=0.1)\n",
        "\n",
        "# 4. GP Regression & Hyperparameter Optimization\n",
        "gp = GaussianProcessRegressor(kernel=kernel, n_restarts_optimizer=10, random_state=42)\n",
        "gp.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
        "\n",
        "# 5. Predict and Evaluate\n",
        "y_pred, y_std = gp.predict(X_test, return_std=True)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Optimized Kernel: {gp.kernel_}\")\n",
        "print(f\"R2 Score (Heating/Cooling): {r2_score(y_test, y_pred, multioutput='raw_values')}\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Non-Parametric Flexibility: The GPR transforms discrete observations into a continuous predictive distribution. It does not just provide a best-fit line; it provides a \"corridor of probability\" indicating the uncertainty of the heating and cooling load estimates.  Correlated Outputs: Modeling both Y1 and Y2 together is effective because heating and cooling loads for the same building geometry are physically correlated. The optimized length-scale from the RBF kernel will reveal how sensitive the loads are to changes in the building shapes (like glazing area and orientation)."
      ],
